Don&#39;t try to return an array of variants. If you do so, you get the error: 

`100315 (P0000): Unsupported return type: com.snowflake.snowpark_java.types.Variant[] in function JAVA_VARIANTS with handler MyClass.myFunction`

Instead, use the fact that a Variant can also be an array, so just return Variant:

```sql
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION java_variants(x variant)
RETURNS variant
LANGUAGE JAVA
PACKAGES = (&#39;com.snowflake:snowpark:1.7.0&#39;)
HANDLER = &#39;MyClass.myFunction&#39;
AS $$
    import java.util.stream.Stream;
    import com.snowflake.snowpark_java.types.Variant;
    public class MyClass {
        public static Variant myFunction(Variant input) {
            return input;
        }
    }
$$;

select java_variants([1, {&#39;a&#39;:3}, &#39;2020-09-12&#39;::date]);

-- [   1,   {     &quot;a&quot;: 3   },   &quot;2020-09-12&quot; ]
```

We can go deeper - for example we can convert the input Variant into an Array, and then convert that Array back into a Variant:

```java
        public static Variant myFunction(Variant input) {
            return new Variant(input.asArray());
        }
```

